WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:08.000
So thank you everyone. My name is David Smith, and I'm a developer advocate at Microsoft.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:17.000
And if you've ever given a tutorial using R or just tried to share R code with other people and gotten these kind of responses, then this talk is for you.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Now you might get these kind of reactions because somebody didn't read the setup instructions or installed the wrong version of R and so your code doesn't work.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Or they're using a different operating system than you expect, or just using an old laptop that can't cope with the data and the code that you provided.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
But you can resolve all these issues by running in something called GitHub Codespaces.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
So let's see how this works.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:44.000
I've got here a repository which you can find on GitHub. It has everything you need to recreate what I'm showing you right here.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
But one of the things that it does include is a .dev container folder.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:55.000
And that is the magic that allows you to click on that code button directly in GitHub and then run the code within Codespaces.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
Now this is running in real time. It takes about 10 or 20 seconds.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:10.000
What GitHub is doing right here is setting up a Codespace, kind of like a little virtual machine that has the version of R that I specified, installs all the R package versions that I specified.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:22.000
It also installs Python, my data, my code, everything is all right there ready for anybody who clicks on the button to get exactly in the environment that I intended for somebody to run my code within.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:29.000
So once that Codespace launches in just a couple of seconds, what we'll see is a web interface that looks much like Visual Studio Code.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.000
And in fact, this is Visual Studio Code running directly within the browser.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.000
And I can do all the usual things like browsing within my file system that comes from my repository.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:49.000
This is actually a tutorial that comes from a collection provided by Microsoft, including a Jupyter notebook, which is to teach somebody how to do data exploration using R.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
So this notebook has popped up directly within Visual Studio Code.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.000
And I can interact with it as you would any other notebook, like I can run this cell right here.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:04.000
And the surprising thing is it runs without any errors, without any setup, because all those packages are already pre-installed within the Codespace.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
So your participants can then interact with the notebook, run the code.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Here's a tidyverse function, which is reading in a data file and showing in the first few lines.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:19.000
It's a very, very natural experience, regardless what kind of laptop that they brought to the workshop with them.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
But what if you wanted to run your workshop within RStudio instead of Visual Studio Code?

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:25.000
That's easy, too.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Because we have RStudio Server installed within this Codespace, just need to go to the Ports tab in Visual Studio Code, and that launches RStudio Server directly within my browser.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
So this is the same as RStudio on the desktop, just running on a browser.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.000
And I can use that to open files.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:44.000
And again, I'm going to open a file from my repository.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
They happen to live in the workspaces folder when it's running on the server.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:49.000
And I browse through that.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:55.000
And this time, let's grab an R Markdown document instead, so we can see how that works within Codespaces.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
There we have our Markdown document.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And we can just use the usual knit function within RStudio to knit it to HTML.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.000
And we can see our output really quickly, because it's running on a machine with lots of RAM, lots of CPU.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
So these computations happen nice and fast.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:18.000
This is all thanks to the magic of DevContainers, which is a standardized way of setting up a container for interactive use like this.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
You saw that DevContainer folder in my repository.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:29.000
That's where I specified the R versions, the packages, and everything else that I needed to give the same experience for every user that interacts with my repo.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.000
DevContainers, by the way, are 100% open source technology.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:38.000
There is a command line interface, so you can integrate those DevContainers into any application, not just GitHub.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
And you can find lots of information about them at containers.dev.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
But just to give you a little bit of a flavor of how that works, if you're familiar with containers, you'll know about Dockerfiles,

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
where you can specify the software that gets installed into that container.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:59.000
In this particular case, I'm grabbing a prebuilt container from the Rocker project, an awesome project providing containers for R.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:07.000
I chose the version of R. In this case, it's grabbing the latest 4.x version, so I got the very newest 4.2.1 for that particular example.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
And I'm installing a bunch of packages into that container as well.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
There's another file that lets you configure Visual Studio code, set some options if people are using that editor.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:23.000
And you can also specify commands to run at the beginning of the container, like starting the RStudio server, which is how we got that to work.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So in summary, if you want to do a tutorial or share some code, just create a GitHub repo as you always do.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:34.000
Put all your scripts, data, notebooks, and instructions into there, but then set it up as a dev container,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.000
so that all the software to run your code is fixed and ready for anybody to use,

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.000
simply by clicking on that Run in GitHub Codespaces button directly in GitHub.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Now, GitHub Codespaces is only available right now within GitHub Enterprise and GitHub Education.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:55.000
If your participants don't have access to Codespaces today, they can run it locally using Visual Studio code.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.000
And I have another talk which shows you how that works, which you can't quite see.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
But you can find that link directly on my GitHub repository that you see on your screen right there,

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
with everything you need to make all this work for you.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Thank you.

